  "prompt": "Is the singularity at the time of the Big Bang thought to be a White Hole?",
  "response": "No, the singularity at the time of the Big Bang is not typically considered a white hole. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Singularity:\n- The Big Bang singularity represents a point of infinite density and temperature\n- It's a theoretical boundary where known physical laws break down\n- It marks the beginning of our observable universe\n\n2. White Hole:\n- A white hole is a hypothetical cosmic region that cannot be entered from the outside\n- It's essentially the opposite of a black hole\n- While mathematically possible, white holes have not been observationally confirmed\n- They would theoretically eject matter and light, rather than absorb them\n\n3. Differences:\n- The Big Bang singularity was an expansion/creation event\n- A white hole would be a localized phenomenon expelling matter\n- They are conceptually different cosmic events\n\n4. Current Understanding:\n- Physicists are still working to understand the exact nature of the Big Bang singularity\n- Theories like quantum gravity aim to explain what happened at this moment\n- The singularity is not currently considered a white hole in mainstream cosmological theory\n\nWhile both concepts involve extreme physics, they are distinct theoretical constructs.",
